[14:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the map is not centered, plus the water bottle is not near the right tire. Whereas for this new method, it got everything correct. So, how they made this is they first created this huge'

[14:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dataset with over 80,000 pairs comparing correct versus incorrect spatial arrangements. For example, here is the prompt and here\'s the correct answer, but they also intentionally edited the image to make it wrong. And then'

[14:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'afterwards, they trained a reward model using this dataset of correct and incorrect pairs. And afterwards, this framework now understands, you know, the spatial arrangement of objects based on your prompt a lot better. The awesome'

[15:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thing is if you scroll up to the top of the page and you click on this GitHub repo, here it says we are planning to release the dataset and the model weights. So, stay tuned for that. If you really care about, you know, the spatial'

[15:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'arrangement of objects in your images, then this might be a good framework to use. Anyways, if you\'re interested, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also this week ByteDance isn\'t done cooking yet, so they also released this crazy tool'

[15:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'called Spectrum. And this is a way to speed up AI image and video generation by predicting future steps instead of actually computing them. So you can basically apply Spectrum on top of any existing video or image workflow. So for'

[15:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'example, here they applied it to Hunyuan video to get it to speed up the generation by like 3.5 times without any loss in quality. And then instead of video, you can also apply Spectrum to an image generator like Flux to also speed'

[15:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up the generation by 3.5 times. So here\'s a comparison with its image generations compared to other acceleration methods, Spectrum is on the far right and as you can see with the same prompt, the quality is pretty much'

[16:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the same as the original Flux generation. But it\'s just that Spectrum is like 4.7 times faster, even faster than the other acceleration methods which introduce a ton of errors in the generation. And then here is a video'

[16:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generation comparison. So on the left is the original video generated with Hunyuan video at 50 steps, in the middle is this new Spectrum generated with only 14 steps so it\'s a 3.5 times increase, and then on the right is another'

[16:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'acceleration called Taylor Seer, but as you can see the quality of this competitor is a lot worse. The colors are a lot more saturated, whereas for Spectrum it\'s really hard to tell this apart from the original generation even'

[16:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'though it\'s a lot faster. And then instead of Hunyuan video, here\'s another test using Wan 2.1. Again, Spectrum is in the middle, a competitor Taylor Seer is on the right, and it just has way too many errors. As you can see here,'

[16:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Spectrum looks almost the same as the original video. So the quality is great, but you can generate this like 3.5 times faster. If you\'re curious on how this works, it basically uses a math technique called the Chebyshev'

[17:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'polynomials to model how features change over time. And it uses this to forecast future steps without spending more compute. So, that makes it a lot faster, but without degrading the quality much. The awesome thing is they\'ve already'

[17:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'released the code to this. So, if you click on this GitHub repo and you scroll down a bit, here it contains all the instructions on how to download and run this locally on your computer. Note that it works for both text-to-image for a'

[17:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ton of different models like Flux and SDXL, as well as text-to-video for Phenaki and Imagen 2.1. Anyways, if you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. I\'ve been covering'

