[18:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, ByteDance just built an AI system that automatically writes faster GPU code for AI. It\'s called CUDA Agent, and this is quite technical, so let\'s break this down in simple terms. You see, most'

[19:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'modern AI systems, like GPT or image models, video generators, they all run on GPUs. And GPUs use special programs called kernels that execute code in parallel really fast. So, a kernel is'

[19:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically a program that runs on a ton of GPU cores at once. But, these are really hard to write and optimize. So, here they\'ve created a tool called CUDA agent, which not only writes out this'

[19:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'GPU code, but it also tests it and measures its speed and improves the quality until it becomes faster and faster. So, it\'s like an AI agent that\'s optimized for writing code for GPUs. And the output of this CUDA agent is'

[19:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually ridiculously good. So, here are some metrics for your reference. Here they\'re comparing it with some of the top models out there, including Gemini 3 Pro and Opus 4.5. But, as you can see, this new CUDA agent is even better at'

[19:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'writing GPU code across all these metrics. So, the correct rate of the GPU code, as well as all these speed metrics, you can see by far it\'s better than the other models. Now, the awesome'

[20:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thing is they\'ve released everything already. So, if you click on this GitHub repo and you scroll down a bit, here it contains the entire data set that they used to train this agent. And then here is the entire agent workflow, so you can'

[20:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'download and try this yourself as well. This is very technical, but it\'s quite a big deal if you\'re into optimizing CUDA kernels to make AI models run faster. So, if you\'re interested, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below.'

[20:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Next up, this AI is super helpful. So, it\'s called Eutonia, and this is a single AI model that understands all types of 3D point cloud data. Now, traditionally, you need to build'

[20:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'separate models for scanning different types of 3D data. For example, self-driving lidar scans would have a separate model from indoor room scans, which would also be separate from like satellite or remote sensing data. But,'

[20:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here Eutonia is one encoder that works across all of them. And this allows the same model to be used for many things like robotics, autonomous driving, virtual reality, spatial reasoning, 3D segmentation, and more. So, as you can'

[21:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'see here, it can work with a ton of different types of point cloud data. This is a unified model that can convert any type of 3D point cloud data, including outdoor lidar data or indoor scans or CAD models, and basically'

[21:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'encode them to be used for downstream tasks. The awesome thing is they\'ve already released this. So, if you click on this GitHub repo and you scroll down a bit, here it contains all the instructions on how to install and run'

[21:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this locally on your computer. Note that this is quite model, so if I click on the hugging face repo, this is only like 550 megabytes in size. Anyways, if you\'re interested in reading further,'

[21:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also this week, we have another video editor called free edit. And this is quite interesting. So, this edits videos by changing the first frame and then having the AI propagate'

[21:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'those changes throughout the rest of the video. For example, we can change the background from this desert hill into some sand castles, and that would just be the first frame. Now, what free edit does is it then applies this background'

[22:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'change to the rest of the video. Or here\'s another example where we can take the first frame of this video and turn the cart to red, and then free edit would make this car red throughout the rest of the video. Now, if you compare'

[22:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this with other video editing methods like go with the flow or ITV edit, etc., notice that this new one, free edit, just performs a lot better. Everything is a lot more consistent. Here\'s another'

[22:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'example for your reference. Now, how this works is it uses something called editing aware REE injection. So, as the diffusion model is generating the video, you can see that it adds these REE'

[22:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'blocks, which basically uses optical flow to track the edited regions across frames. And then it adaptively controls how much of the original video gets edited with the new features. Unfortunately for this one, they haven\'t'

[22:56] [scene:talk]
